@arg repository-transition/job-argument
@title Repository Transition Job Argument
@sigils [👉/义 🌹/门]
@instantiated-by ["(Slide 1) We ARE {Depositors, Downloaders, Governors," "Assessors, Archivists, Students} AND we BELIEVE in" "{Inclusivity, Confidence, Enterprising Creativity," "Connectedness, Generosity of Spirit}."]
@illustrates ["Leadership does not require heavy machinery; only a process" "for turning tensions into requirements."]
@instantiated-by ["(Slide 2) PCE = Strategy, Responsibility, Connectivity," "Inclusivity, Development — the operational “output space.”"]
@instantiated-by ["(Slide 3) Transformation Cycle:" "Surface tensions & signals" "Elicit minimum viable requirements" "Publish transparent workflows" "Listen lightly (micro-feedback)" "Iterate in a safe operating zone"]
@specifies "OBU values → motivation, culture, purpose"
@specifies "PCE criteria → constraints, governance, performance"
@specifies "Pattern-based tension analysis → method for bridging the two"

! conclusion: A repository transition is best led using a lightweight, iterative [👉/义 🌹/门]
              identity→projection→capability process.

  + THEN: Operate an explicit move on the named axis (see substructure below); steward the pattern against the declared discipline.
    + underpinned-by: This model aligns with OBU identity AND with PCE capability
                      expectations.

  + because: Repository behaviour emerges from stakeholders acting through the
             university’s guiding principles.

  + because: Identity alone does not determine behaviour; it is always projected
             into PCE-defined capability dimensions.

  + because: These tensions can be used as design signals with a simple,
             repeatable leadership pattern.
